net_analyzer

Introduction

I coded net_analyzer to have a quick way to get an overview of a network capture in pcap format. The first version was in python3, because I started to use the application in my work more and more, I coded it in rust. In the following, I will give an overview and show how net_analyzer works.

Try it Out

# build and copy the executable
cargo build --release
cp target/release/netanalyze .

# bootstrap
./bootstrap.sh

# convert pcap to csv
cd captures
./conv_csv.sh test.pcap
cd ..

# run
./netanalyze captures/test.pcap.csv report

# visualize
cd py 
python3 visualize.py

# the results
ls -l ../results

Getting Started

First of all, build net_analyzer with cargo build --release. You get the executable netanalyze in target/release/.

When you clone the repo, you should first run bootstrap.sh. Currently, this just creates a directory where analysis results are saved. Then you put your pcap to analyze in the captures folder. There is already a sample pcap there and the script conv_csv.sh. This will use tshark to convert your pcap into csv format with the fields in the correct order for net_analyzer to work with.

Analyzing a Capture

Running netanalyzer gives you the usage:

./netanalyze 
USAGE:   netanalyze [PATH-TO-CSV-FILE] [NAME-OF-REPORT]
Example: netanalyze captures/test.csv report
-- to convert to CSV with the correct headers,
-- use the script "captures/conv_csv.sh"
./netanalyze 
USAGE:   netanalyze [PATH-TO-CSV-FILE] [NAME-OF-REPORT]
Example: netanalyze captures/test.csv report
-- to convert to CSV with the correct headers,
-- use the script "captures/conv_csv.sh"

All you need to do is supply a path to a converted pcap file into the csv format with the script mentioned in Getting Started and the name of the report file.

Let's try this with a malware traffic capture:

./netanalyze captures/2020-10-30-Emotet-to-Qakbot-to-Emotet.pcap.csv qakbot

-- read 10000 packets

The report contains:

  • all ip communications
  • all communications via layer 2
  • observed ports
  • observed protocol names
  • ip:port to ip:port communications

Conclusion

The graphs may get messy for large amounts of hosts, but for getting a general overview of the network structure, it's nice to have. The generated report can be grepped or analyzed manually.

Changes and improvements will be made over time.
